[[File:Bornö havsforskningsstation 3.jpg|thumb|Bornö Marine Research Station]]
'''Bornö Marine Research Station''', owned by the '''Bornö Institute for Ocean and Climate Studies''',<ref name="Bornö Institute" /> is located at [[Holma, Lysekil Municipality|Holma]] on the island [[Stora Bornö]] in [[Gullmarsfjorden]], about {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Gothenburg]], Sweden. It was built in 1902 by {{Interlanguage link multi|Otto Pettersson|sv}} and {{Interlanguage link multi|Gustaf Ekman|sv|3=Gustaf Ekman (1852–1930)}}, both pioneers of Swedish marine research.{{sfn|Leppäranta|Myrberg|2009|p=17}} The station was originally built in response to the agreements of the [[International Council for the Exploration of the Sea]] (ICES) signed in Copenhagen in 1902 between [[Denmark]], [[Finland]], [[Germany]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Sweden]], [[Russia]], and the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=members>{{cite web|title=Our history|url=http://www.ices.dk/explore-us/who-we-are/Pages/Our-history.aspx|publisher=International Council for the Exploration of the Sea|accessdate=8 January 2016|location=Copenhagen, Denmark}}</ref> The station was built with funding from Pettersson and Ekman, on Pettersson's land, and then rented to the Swedish Hydrographic Biological Commission (SHBK) to conduct studies on oceans and climate. In 1931, Pettersson's son [[Hans Pettersson|Hans]], who was a professor at the [[University of Gothenburg]] expanded the research on the island and then in 1932 the SHBK was able to purchase the island for the government.<ref name="Börnö Station">{{cite web|last1=Andersson|first1=Eugenia|title=Börnö Station|url=http://ipd.gu.se/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=404490&languageId=100001&contentId=-1|publisher=University of Gothenburg|accessdate=8 January 2016|location=Gothenburg, Sweden|date=27 August 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125074026/http://ipd.gu.se/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=404490&languageId=100001&contentId=-1#|archive-date=2016-01-25|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>

The island has been considered by many Swedes to be the birthplace of Swedish oceanography.<ref name="Bornö Institute">{{cite web|title=Bornö Institute for Ocean and Climate Studies|url=http://www.bornoinstitute.o.se/ENGELSKA.HTM|publisher=Bornö Institute|accessdate=8 January 2016|location=Bornö, Sweden}}</ref> Beginning in 1908, Otto Pettersson collected daily records on the temperature and salinity of the waters at the Bornö Station.<ref name="Börnö Station" /> With few interruptions, mostly during conflicts in World War I and World War II, these daily observations continued until the 1980s.{{sfn|Fonselius|2001|p=115}} Petterson also discovered internal tidal waves by studying variations of the boundary surfaces between the brackish and ocean waters, which led him to develop a photographic current meter.{{sfn|Fonselius|2001|p=116}} When his son took over the investigations at the institute in the 1930s, he began to focus on the radioactive dating of sediments{{sfn|Fonselius|2001|p=119}} and forged research collaborations with the scientists at the [[Institute for Radium Research, Vienna|Institute for Radium Research of Vienna]].{{sfn|Rentetzi|2004|p=360}}

The station grounds, covering {{convert|19000|m2|abbr=on}}, are a nature reserve.<ref name="Börnö Station" /> It is currently owned and operated by a foundation named the Bornö Institute for Ocean and Climate Studies and provides educational facilities for the University of Gothenburg. It is also available to let to companies or organizations for field courses, research, instrument development or national and international meetings.<ref name="Bornö Institute" />

The upper floors contain eight bedrooms housing 15 beds, as well as two kitchens. On the ground floor are four office spaces and a lecture hall with accommodations for 25 people.<ref name="Bornö Institute" />
