{{Infobox organization | image = KinoBorder.png | caption = | motto = | predecessor = | merged = | successor = | formation = | extinction = | type = | status = | purpose = Refugee service | headquarters = Nogales, Arizona | coords = | language = Spanish/English | leader_title = Executive Director | leader_name = Sean Carroll | leader_title2 = | leader_name2 = | leader_name3 = | leader_title3 = | leader_title4 = | leader_name4 = | key_people = | main_organ = | parent_organization = | affiliations = [[Jesuit]] & [[Catholic church|Catholic]] | budget = $700,000 per year<ref name="cronk">{{Cite news|url=http://cronkitenewsonline.com/2014/10/kino-border-initiative-eases-transition-back-to-mexico-for-those-deported-through-nogales|title=Initiative eases transition back to Mexico for those deported through Nogales|access-date=2017-02-20|language=en-US}}</ref> | remarks = 6 founders +14 partner | name = Kino Border Initiative | former name = | image_border = | size = 150 | abbreviation = | merger = | established = {{Start date and age|2008}} | location = | region_served = Mexico & Central America | membership = Open to all | general = | num_staff = 15<ref name="prog">{{Cite news|url=https://www.kinoborderinitiative.org/programs/education|title=Education - Kino Border Initiative|newspaper=Kino Border Initiative|access-date=2017-02-20|language=en-US}}</ref> | num_volunteers = | website = [https://www.kinoborderinitiative.org KBI.org] }}
'''Kino Border Initiative (KBI)''' since 2008 has united six [[Catholic church|Catholic]] organizations in an effort to be a humanizing presence and to foster bi-national solidarity on the issue of migration on the U.S.-Mexico border through direct assistance and accompaniment, education, research, and advocacy.
==History== In 2008 and 2009 in [[Nogales, Arizona]], and [[Nogales, Sonora]], Mexico, this work was begun by six organizations: the California Province of the [[Society of Jesus]], [[Jesuit Refugee Service]]/USA, the Missionary Sisters of the Eucharist, the Mexican Province of the Society of Jesus, the [[Diocese of Tucson]], and the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Hermosillo|Archdiocese of Hermosillo]]. Its purpose is to break down barriers to humane, just, and workable migration, affirming human dignity and solidarity. KBI gives direct assistance and accompanies migrants, educates communities on both sides of the border, and collaborates with networks of research and advocacy to transform policy at all levels of government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asucatholic.org/MissionTrip|title=Mission Trip|website=All Saints Catholic Newman Center|language=en|access-date=2017-02-20}}</ref> It sees its work in continuity with the historic record of the USA in welcoming immigrants, and in support of international standards for the treatment of refugees.
